    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><strong>RBF neural networks</strong> are actually FF (feed forward) NNs, that use <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radial_basis_function" target="_self">radial basis function</a> as activation function instead of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_function" target="_self">logistic function</a>. What makes the difference?</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Logistic function map some arbitrary value to a 0…1 range, answering a “yes or no” question. It is good for classification and decision making systems, but works bad for continuous values.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Contrary, radial basis functions answer the question “how far are we from the target”? This is perfect for function approximation, and machine control (as a replacement of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PID_controller" target="_self">PID</a> controllers, for example).</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">To be short, these are just FF networks with different activation function and appliance.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
